Buttery to the touch and engineered to perform, NikeSKIMS Studio Stretch brings a fashion-first sensibility to the studio. Crafted with sweat-wicking Dri-FIT technology and Lycra Adaptiv to move with you and retain shape, the collection offers gentle compression and support without compromising comfort. From sculpting waistbands to minimal seams and thoughtfully placed straps, every detail has been considered.
Rendered in a palette of linen, dark roast and obsidian, NikeSKIMS Studio Stretch is designed to move effortlessly through every stretch, flow and recovery.
@ployridaa wears #NikeSKIMS Studio Stretch and Stretch Nylon throughout.
@nikewomen @skims #BAZAARpartner

@rosalia.vt is carrying #JonathanAnderson’s vision for @dior beyond the catwalk—or, perhaps more fittingly, pirouetting it onto the stage.
At the Boston stop of her #Lux tour, the Spanish star wore a quartet of custom ensembles by the designer, turning her performance into a live study of Anderson’s evolving Dior codes. For a rendition of “Porcelana,” Rosalía emerged in a bespoke tutu dress, composed of a ribbed knit tank top embellished with ivory beads and a structured organza skirt with a perfectly tattered hemline. To complete the balletcore look, Rosalía wore white pointe shoes, a choice that was practical as much as aesthetic. (The 25-song set includes ballet and various dance styles.)
The Dior showcased at Rosalía’s concert tied—naturally—directly into the visual language Anderson is shaping at the house. Tap the link in bio for a deeper look into the singer and designer’s latest partnership.

Nobody ever changed the game by following the script. Nike’s latest football campaign, Rip the Script, champions exactly this idea. Featuring everyone from Kylian Mbappé and Vini Jr. to Cristiano Ronaldo, the campaign is part football film, part cultural spectacle—and a reminder that the game is at its best when it’s creative, joyful and unpredictable.
@Nike @Nikefootball
#PaidPartnership

@_fox_lab_ has tapped @wearebraindead for a 17-piece capsule that brings the spirit of ’90s Southern California motocross into everyday wear. ⁠
⁠
Ahead of the launch, Fox Lab and Brain Dead unveiled a custom race kit worn by Ken Roczen, who went on to claim the 2026 AMA Supercross 450SX Championship in Salt Lake City. The title marked a historic milestone for both Roczen and Fox Racing, making the 32-year-old rider the oldest premier-class champion and the rider with the longest gap between his professional debut and first championship win. ⁠

@kappa continues to occupy a unique space in football, turning underdogs into style icons through its unmistakable design language. While the major sportswear brands unveiled their 2026 World Cup kits months ago, Kappa arrives fashionably late with Tunisia's tournament collection, proving once again that it remains football's go-to label for the game's best-dressed teams.⁠
⁠
The North African nation will take to the pitch in a clean white home kit with center-aligned badges and subtle grey sleeve detailing, complemented by a red away strip and a sleek black third option accented with red touches. Beyond the matchday uniforms, Kappa's retro-inspired apparel steals the spotlight, featuring oversized "TUNISIA" branding across polos, tees, and track jackets. Shot with the brand's signature fashion-editorial approach and featuring local talent alongside football-obsessed youngsters, the campaign perfectly captures the nostalgic charm Kappa has made its trademark.⁠

After sharing part one of our fave Ukrainian brands, our comment section was filled with loads more suggestions from you guys. As requested, swipe through to see part 2 of the list, featuring all of your recommendations.
